(18, 'FIRST TANAY PHOTO EXHIBIT OPENS, FINALIST OF TANAY PHOTO CONTEST ANNOUNCED', 'first-tanay-photo-exhibit-opens-finalist-of-tanay-photo-contest-announced', '<p>November 4, 2015 - As part of the Pre-Hane Festival Activity the First Tanay Photo Exhibit formally opened &nbsp;its doors to the public. Attending the ribbon cutting ceremony were Mayor Rafael “Lito” Tanjuatco, Vice Mayor Jimmy Vista, Municipal Administrator Dr. Gabriel Piguing, Tanay Tourism Office Head, Mr. Jeffrey Pino, Tanay Legal Department Head, Atty. Amadeo Fulgado, Mutya ng Tanay 2014 Winners and the Chairman/Founder of Tanay Photography Club Beethhoven Mendez together with the members of Tanay Photography Club and the participants of Tanay Photography Contest 2015.</p><p><img src=\"https://scontent-hkg3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xfp1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12193846_10203781220651302_3702012609868539030_n.jpg?oh=425276940adfe629cb67ede862e70239&amp;oe=56AD7F06\" alt=\"\" width=\"584\" height=\"389\" data-mce-src=\"https://scontent-hkg3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xfp1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12193846_10203781220651302_3702012609868539030_n.jpg?oh=425276940adfe629cb67ede862e70239&amp;oe=56AD7F06\"></p><p>The exhibit features the photos from the local and overseas members of Tanay Photography Club and the all entries of Tanay Photography Contest 2015.</p><p><img src=\"https://fbcdn-sphotos-h-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xfp1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12187846_10203781213171115_8385465563592027414_n.jpg?oh=41ad9284b84a88614a8e7b1700d0c8a0&amp;oe=56CA62EB&amp;__gda__=1455604242_cc6bb1eece86be4ef666a28d014e78d3\" alt=\"\" width=\"584\" height=\"389\" data-mce-src=\"https://fbcdn-sphotos-h-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xfp1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12187846_10203781213171115_8385465563592027414_n.jpg?oh=41ad9284b84a88614a8e7b1700d0c8a0&amp;oe=56CA62EB&amp;__gda__=1455604242_cc6bb1eece86be4ef666a28d014e78d3\"></p><p>A Certificate of Participation was given to all the participants during the event as well as the hand-over of a collage photo created by Tanay Photography Club for the Mayor.</p><p><img src=\"https://scontent-hkg3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xap1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12193741_10203781231691578_8253530087727548783_n.jpg?oh=89d663861eb5ff36acf0b8f96e622f92&amp;oe=56AE5F84\" alt=\"\" width=\"552\" height=\"368\" data-mce-src=\"https://scontent-hkg3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xap1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12193741_10203781231691578_8253530087727548783_n.jpg?oh=89d663861eb5ff36acf0b8f96e622f92&amp;oe=56AE5F84\"></p><p><img src=\"https://fbcdn-sphotos-c-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xpa1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12108831_10203781229011511_211950661760221283_n.jpg?oh=d58c9f496e968b91f33c2828f9782579&amp;oe=56C6A202&amp;__gda__=1455370695_a86d51c3305ed2e8aa1ba74fa4a763a4\" alt=\"\" width=\"581\" height=\"387\" data-mce-src=\"https://fbcdn-sphotos-c-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xpa1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/12108831_10203781229011511_211950661760221283_n.jpg?oh=d58c9f496e968b91f33c2828f9782579&amp;oe=56C6A202&amp;__gda__=1455370695_a86d51c3305ed2e8aa1ba74fa4a763a4\"></p><p>The official announcement of the finalists for the Tanay Photography Contest was also held during the event. The finalists were Mr. Muhammad Arif Sheva for his curved road photo in Mayagay, Mr. Aldrick Lagmay for his Kinabuan Falls photo and Mr. Spencer S. Ross for his Mapatag Plateau photo.</p><p><img src=\"https://fbcdn-sphotos-d-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xlf1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/11205056_10203781234211641_4750835118229638549_n.jpg?oh=a3b5bd0bc033496dafd3aa700beddf1c&amp;oe=56BF6E21&amp;__gda__=1454154173_9bf946d9396979669781cde042cc14e2\" alt=\"\" width=\"561\" height=\"374\" data-mce-src=\"https://fbcdn-sphotos-d-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-xlf1/v/t1.0-9/s720x720/11205056_10203781234211641_4750835118229638549_n.jpg?oh=a3b5bd0bc033496dafd3aa700beddf1c&amp;oe=56BF6E21&amp;__gda__=1454154173_9bf946d9396979669781cde042cc14e2\"></p><p>The three finalists were invited to attend the Gabi ng Parangal on Nov. 12, 2015, 6PM @ Tanay Municipal Grounds where the announcement of the winner will be held.</p><p><br></p><p>Written by: Mike Anthony Catuira&nbsp;</p><p>Photos by Beethhoven Mendez full photo available here: &nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/beethhoven.mendez/media_set?set=a.10203781211891083.1073741890.1842717122&amp;type=3\" data-mce-href=\"https://www.facebook.com/beethhoven.mendez/media_set?set=a.10203781211891083.1073741890.1842717122&amp;type=3\">https://www.facebook.com/beethhoven.mendez/media_set?set=a.10203781211891083.1073741890.1842717122&amp;type=3</a></p><p><a href=\"http://www.tanay.gov.ph/about-tanay/news-events/121-first-tanay-photo-exhibit-opens-finalist-of-tanay-photo-contest-announced\">http://www.tanay.gov.ph/about-tanay/news-events/121-first-tanay-photo-exhibit-opens-finalist-of-tanay-photo-contest-announced</a></p><p><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></p>', 'festival', '#PhotoContest', 1, 6, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 5, 1),
(19, 'CALINAWAN CAVE', 'calinawan-cave', '<p><img src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7319/9809841185_beb9b04121_b.jpg\" alt=\"Image result for calinawan cave\" data-mce-src=\"http://farm8.staticflickr.com/7319/9809841185_beb9b04121_b.jpg\" width=\"343\" height=\"251\"></p><p>Calinawan Cave is one of the most accessable destination from the metro that will give you an&nbsp;entirely&nbsp;different air. I, personally can\'t believe that I just travel a couple of hours to reach such tranquil spot -&nbsp;a very promising destination that makes me&nbsp;wander more. Wander if we can add more years to these places\' life span?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Calinawan cave is a cave found in Brgy. Tandang, Kutyo, Tanay Rizal - it is named after the historical event where&nbsp;Filipino settled and agreed on their disputes&nbsp;between Spanish&nbsp;Revolutionaries, the agreement promises&nbsp;<em>\"linaw\"&nbsp;</em>a&nbsp;Filipino word for clarity (the bisayan word \"kalinawan\" means \"peace\" suits very well too)<em>.</em>&nbsp;From what&nbsp;I have seen, the part that was opened for spelunking is just a small part - and yes it is, according to our guide the cave is composed of&nbsp;seven levels and only two were open as the others are not yet explored. The cave was privately managed until&nbsp; last year (2012)when they collaborated with DOT.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><strong>&nbsp;http://www.senyoritalakwachera.com/2013/09/calinawan-cave-tanay-rizal.html</strong></p>', 'places', '#CalinawanCave', 1, 9, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 4, 1),
(20, 'TANAY RODEO FESTIVAL', 'tanay-rodeo-festival', '<p><img src=\"http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-3wRssEEQMZw/VKyjN8yyi3I/AAAAAAAAAGQ/B9p7DAO2xBQ/s1600/Rodeo%2BFestival.jpg\" alt=\"Image result for tanay rodeo festival\" data-mce-src=\"http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-3wRssEEQMZw/VKyjN8yyi3I/AAAAAAAAAGQ/B9p7DAO2xBQ/s1600/Rodeo%2BFestival.jpg\" width=\"350\" height=\"250\"></p><p>To promote and market the town’s cattle and agri-eco tourism not only within the&nbsp; municipality but also in the CALABARZON&nbsp; region, the Municipal Government of Tanay holds Tanay Rodeo every third week of January each year.</p><p>The festival is also in line with the celebration of Tanay Town Fiesta. It is participated by professionals and rodeo enthusiasts, and veterinary/animal science students from renowned universities in the country.</p><p><span style=\"color: #0070c0;\" data-mce-style=\"color: #0070c0;\"><a href=\"http://tanay.gov.ph/for-visitors/tourist-information/2015-07-10-03-46-25/tanay-rodeo-festival\" data-mce-href=\"http://tanay.gov.ph/for-visitors/tourist-information/2015-07-10-03-46-25/tanay-rodeo-festival\">http://tanay.gov.ph/for-visitors/tourist-information/2015-07-10-03-46-25/tanay-rodeo-festival</a></span></p>', 'culture', '#RodeoFestival', 1, 2, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(21, 'SANGAB CAVE', 'sangab-cave', '<p><img src=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-A0OuHyuMdik/WS02l8f7H2I/AAAAAAAACqk/p3IA3HFhULQ5EfKtxI920lW_THYycne9QCEw/s640/Cave%2Bentrance%2BSangab.jpg\" width=\"350\" height=\"250\" data-mce-src=\"https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-A0OuHyuMdik/WS02l8f7H2I/AAAAAAAACqk/p3IA3HFhULQ5EfKtxI920lW_THYycne9QCEw/s640/Cave%2Bentrance%2BSangab.jpg\"></p><div>The Tanay town is one of the ideal getaway to mingle with nature. For it\'s proximity to metrocity, Tanay is a best Tagaytay alternative especially during weekend. Like in Tagaytay, it also posses a refreshing mountain scenery, and cooler climate. And Sangab Cave is only one among many tourist destination in Tanay.</div><div><br></div><div>Situated at Brgy. Sta. Ines in the town of Tanay, province of Rizal, just near the road. What makes this cave a unique among other is the entrance submerge under water. Perfect hide out during zombie apocalyse in the Philippines. Ok, enough for the zombie thing.</div><div><br></div><div>Sangab Cave posses a centuries old stalagmite and stalactite formation and underground river! Water is clear and cold, perfect for a swim. Aside from some water activity this place also perfect for a camping. You can set a tent adjacent to the cave. This place is also a rich biodiversity of wild animals, insects, birds, and plants, so it\'s a wise choice to bring something that can protect you from harm especially at night.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>During the night, the place was really peaceful and the weather is really cold. In the morning a happily chirping birds will wake you and the beautiful streak of fog hovered across the valley will greet you.&nbsp;</div><div><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></div><div>http://www.herjcjane.com/2017/05/sangab-cave-and-underground-river-tanay.html</div>', 'places', '#SangabCave<3', 1, 9, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 4, 1),
(22, 'Mt. BATOLUSONG SEA OF CLOUDS : HEAVEN\'S GATE IN TANAY', 'mt-batolusong-sea-of-clouds-heavens-gate-in-tanay', '<p><img src=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-z1Hjqn-QODU/WS5khuBi3nI/AAAAAAAACrc/5fU_J77beyoaW0g7m_mLHA4x9rfdrHHSQCLcB/s640/Mt.%2BBatolusong%2BSea%2Bof%2BClouds%2BHeaven%2527s%2BGate%2Bin%2BTanay%2B%252836%2529.jpg\" width=\"403\" height=\"235\" alt=\"\"><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></p><div>Mt. Batolusong is one of a newly discover hiking destination and spurring a spate of local hiker\'s interest since 2012. Situated in the southern part of the Sierra Madre mountain range in town of Tanay province of Rizal.&nbsp;</div><div><br></div><div>Recomended entry point is either Sitio Kay-ibon, Brgy. Cuyambay, along the Marcos highway or Brgy. San Andres, passing through some interesting rock formations. Either entry going up the Mt. Batolusong summit (Mapatag Plateau) offer a relaxing view of greenery and fresh cool air.</div><div><br></div><div>Going up the mountain by traversing through rice fields, wooded areas, and beautiful rock formations. Near the end of the trail is Mapatag plateau at 645 meters above sea level. The Mapatag Plateau is a summit of Mt. Batolusong which is your final hike destination. The plateau is a grassland slope that serves as a scenic viewpoint and a best spot for a campsite. However, if your looking for more exciting hike, then dare to continue up the trail to Susong Dalaga peak at 780 MASL where you can possibly catch a glimpse of Mounts Banahaw and San Cristobal.<br><br><strong>Where is&nbsp;Mt. Batolusong?</strong><br>The sea of clouds or heaven\'s gate of Tanay si situated in the southern part of the Sierra Madre mountain range in town of Tanay province of Rizal. Point of entry is either in Sitio Kay-ibon of Brgy. Cuyambay or in Brgy. San Andres.<br><strong><br></strong><strong>What to do in&nbsp;Mt. Batolusong?</strong></div><div>The mountain is a perfect hiking destination for and camp site to witness this beautiful picturesque of the sea of clouds.<br></div><p>http://www.herjcjane.com/2017/05/mt-batolusong-sea-of-clouds-heavens.html</p>', 'places', '#SeaClouds', 1, 10, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 4, 1),
(23, 'RAMBULL’S BAKAHAN SA TANAY: FOR THE “COBOY” IN YOU.', 'rambulls-bakahan-sa-tanay-for-the-coboy-in-you', '<p>The road of Tanay, Rizal is often ventured by the adventurous. It is the portal to many natural wonders such as the Daranak Falls, Palo Alto Falls, Masungi Natural Reserve, Calinawan Cave, and so much more! Tanay is also known as the refuge of art and culture. You will see man-made wonders like the 71-foot high statue of the Queen of the Holy Rosary, the Tanay Church, and a dozen more art galleries that prove how the people of Tanay are not only talented but persevering in the preservation of their work. The roads of Tanay Rizal can also induce an elaborate feeling of hunger. Really! And what would be more strategic than finding&nbsp;<strong>Rambulls Bakahan sa Tanay</strong>&nbsp;along the road’s shoulder?</p><p><img src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_115923-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" alt=\"20170611_115923 (2)_marked\" data-mce-src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_115923-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" width=\"416\" height=\"250\"></p><p><strong>Rambulls Bakahan sa Tanay</strong>&nbsp;is so hard to miss. The place looks like a saloon that just popped out of a Western Cowboy movie. &nbsp;With it swinging doors and an endless display of cow skulls, you would know from the outside that you are in for a treat. Plus, it is so hard not to be drawn to it with its numerous vehicles parked outside. That in itself is a sign that they serve good food.</p><p><img src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_115636-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" alt=\"20170611_115636 (2)_marked\" data-mce-src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_115636-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" width=\"395\" height=\"249\"></p><p><img src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_121226-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" alt=\"20170611_121226 (2)_marked\" data-mce-src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_121226-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" width=\"395\" height=\"253\"></p><p>We were seated on the far right side of the restaurant. The place was buzzing with excited chattering and we were all caught in anticipation. We stood in line and patiently waited for our orders to be taken.&nbsp;<strong>Rambulls Bakahan sa Tanay</strong>&nbsp;adopts the&nbsp;<em>turo-turo&nbsp;</em>restaurant format. This adds to the place’s appeal. You can see the food about to be served. I was staring at the&nbsp;<em>Balbakwa</em>&nbsp;for the longest time!</p><p><img src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_121329-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" alt=\"20170611_121329 (2)_marked\" data-mce-src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_121329-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" width=\"402\" height=\"253\"></p><p><img src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_121312-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" alt=\"20170611_121312 (2)_marked\" data-mce-src=\"https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.files.wordpress.com/2017/06/20170611_121312-2_marked.jpg?w=634\" width=\"404\" height=\"356\"></p><p>We ordered Bulalo, Beef Steak, and Kalderetang Kambing. The taste was absolutely commendable. We even concluded how the meat is slowly cooked under crisp firewood. It almost melts in your mouth! We paired it with a tower of iced tea and were more than gracious for the good food.</p><p><span class=\"w8qArf\"><a class=\"fl\" href=\"https://www.google.com.ph/search?rlz=1C1EKKP_enPH773PH773&amp;q=rambulls+bakahan+sa+tanay+address&amp;stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAOPgE-LVT9c3NEwys8xOysgp0pLNTrbSz8lPTizJzM-DM6wSU1KKUouLAaJ8Gh8wAAAA&amp;ludocid=17393934306813026710&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwj21qek_N_dAhVN57wKHdv0AcIQ6BMwFXoECAoQIA\" data-ved=\"2ahUKEwj21qek_N_dAhVN57wKHdv0AcIQ6BMwFXoECAoQIA\" data-mce-href=\"https://www.google.com.ph/search?rlz=1C1EKKP_enPH773PH773&amp;q=rambulls+bakahan+sa+tanay+address&amp;stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAOPgE-LVT9c3NEwys8xOysgp0pLNTrbSz8lPTizJzM-DM6wSU1KKUouLAaJ8Gh8wAAAA&amp;ludocid=17393934306813026710&amp;sa=X&amp;ved=2ahUKEwj21qek_N_dAhVN57wKHdv0AcIQ6BMwFXoECAoQIA\">Address</a>:&nbsp;</span><span class=\"LrzXr\">Manila E Rd, Tanay, Rizal</span></p><p><br></p><p>https://jannispaghettiisawanderlust.wordpress.com/2017/06/24/rambulls-bakahan-sa-tanay-for-the-coboy-in-you/</p><p><br></p>', 'cuisine', '#RambullsBakahan', 1, 1, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 5, 1),
(24, 'KAINAN SA TABING LAWA', 'kainan-sa-tabing-lawa', '<p><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8162/7603316782_a324b0b36c.jpg\" alt=\"2012-06-24 Kainan sa Tabing Lawa LR (6)\" data-mce-src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8162/7603316782_a324b0b36c.jpg\" width=\"384\" height=\"252\"></p><p><img src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8427/7603323464_b14c0b74d0.jpg\" alt=\"2012-06-24 Kainan sa Tabing Lawa LR (12)\" data-mce-src=\"http://farm9.staticflickr.com/8427/7603323464_b14c0b74d0.jpg\" width=\"388\" height=\"354\"></p><p>Kainan sa Tabing Lawa is located at #6 Lakeshore Drive corner Cong. Ding Tanjuatco Streets, Tanay, Rizal. To go there by car, it would be best to take the Manila East Road from Ortigas Extension (Cainta and Taytay). Tanay is the town after Morong and Baras and before Pililia. Turn right towards E. Rodriguez Ave. and left at M. H. del Pilar St. which will take you to the town church. Then, just right after San Ildefonso Church ans Tanay Park, turn right at P. Burgos St. (I think it’s now called Cong. Ding Tanjuatco although it’s still P. Burgos in my Google Maps). Just drive straight through that road until you reach the lakeside. There’s a basketball gym just across the restaurant.</p><div class=\"title\">Location and Contact Information</div><div class=\"content\"><ul class=\"detailsContent\"><li><div class=\"detail\">Address:&nbsp;<span class=\"format_address\"><span class=\"street-address\"># 6 Lakeshore Drive corner Cong. Ding Tanjuatco Street</span>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<span class=\"extended-address\">Brgy. San Isidro</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"locality\">Tanay, Luzon 1980,&nbsp;</span><span class=\"country-name\">Philippines</span></span></div></li><li><div class=\"detail\">Location:&nbsp;Asia&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Philippines&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Luzon&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Calabarzon Region&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Rizal Province&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Tanay</div></li><li><div class=\"detail\">Phone Number:&nbsp;+63 908 451 8578</div></li></ul><p><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></p><p>https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Restaurant_Review-g2336235-d4305783-Reviews-Kainan_sa_Tabing_Lawa-Tanay_Rizal_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon.html</p></div>', 'cuisine', '#KainanSaTabingLawa', 1, 2, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 5, 1),
(25, 'TANAY AND THE AMERICAN REVOLUTION', 'tanay-and-the-american-revolution', '<p><strong>Tanay and the American Revolution</strong></p><p>When the Philippine – American war broke out, the Americans invaded Antipolo which was the provincial capital back then. This forced the provincial government to be transferred to Tanay.</p><p>A year after the fall of Tanay, the provinces of Morong and Manila were merged into one and named “Lalawigan ng Rizal” (Province of Rizal). Baras was still part of Tanay in 1906.&nbsp; However, it became independent and was declared as a separate town in 1920.</p>', 'history', '#TanayDuringAmericanRevolution', 1, 3, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(26, 'TANAY DURING THE  PHILIPPINE REVOLUTION', 'tanay-during-the-philippine-revolution', '<p><strong>Philippine Revolution</strong></p><p>Tanay figured significantly during the revolution against the Spain. During this period, the town was the second zone of the military arm of the Philippine Revolutionary Government under Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo. A “primera compana” composed of Tanayans was organized to augment the government forces under Gen.&nbsp; Aguinaldo.</p>', 'history', '#TanayDuringthePhilippineRevolution', 1, 4, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(27, 'TANAY AND THE JAPANESE OCCUPATION ', 'tanay-and-the-japanese-occupation', '<p>During the Japanese occupation, a number of guerilla units came out in Rizal towns. The very prominent ones were the Hunters ROTC and Marking Guerillas. These guerilla forces fought and incessantly harassed the Japanese occupiers who committed many atrocities against the people. The Japanese enforced the “sona”, a practice wherein the male adults were forcibly gathered inside the church for interrogation. In March 1945, during the invasion of the American forces, the Japanese forced the local people to evacuate the town to avoid being caught in the crossfire. Most of houses in the town plaza including the municipal building (now the site of the Tanay Park) were burned because of the air raids.&nbsp; Tanay was liberated in mid March of 1945.</p><p>Philippine Independence from American colonization was declared in July 4, 1946. Back then the Province of Rizal had twenty six (26) towns including Tanay.</p>', 'history', '#TanayandtheJapaneseOccupation', 1, 5, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(28, 'PRESIDENTIAL DECREE NO. 824', 'presidential-decree-no-824', '<p><strong>Presidential Decree No. 824</strong></p><p>In November 7, 1975, the Metro Manila Commission (MMC) was created under Presidential Decree No. 824. Such creation brought significant changes in the administrative set – up of the Provincial Government of Rizal. Twelve (12) of the original twenty six (26) towns of Rizal Province were severed from their mother province and were made part of the Greater Manila Area. These towns were placed under the administrative supervision of the Commission. This act reduced the Rizal into a province consisting of only fourteen (14) towns, Tanay included.&nbsp; Tanay, Rizal became a first class municipality in 1996.</p>', 'history', '#FirstClassMunicipality', 1, 6, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(29, 'PRE-SPANISH OCCUPATION', 'pre-spanish-occupation', '<p><strong>Pre-Spanish Occupation</strong></p><p>Like most of the inhabitants of the Philippines, the first settlers of Tanaycame from the South Sea, particularly the Malay and Indonesian race. The original Tanay settlers stayed in Daraetan for a long time due to abundance of wild life deer, baboy damo, musang, alamid and monkeys.</p><p><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></p>', 'history', '#Pre-Spanish Occupation', 1, 10, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(30, 'SPANISH OCCUPATION', 'spanish-occupation', '<p><strong>Spanish Occupation</strong></p><p>Monte Tan-ay, now known as INALSAN, was the first known settlement when the Spaniards arrived in 1571. The inhabitants fiercely resisted Christianization by the Spaniards. Beginning from 1573, Monte Tan-Ay formed part of and was under the jurisdiction of Pililla.</p>', 'history', '#SpanishOccupation', 1, 11, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(31, 'ECCLESIASTICAL INDEPENDENCE OF TANAY FROM PILILLA AND OTHE EVENTS IN 1606', 'ecclesiastical-independence-of-tanay-from-pililla-and-othe-events-in-1606', '<p>Tan-ay was still in Inalsan when a separate parish was created by the Spanish Ecclesiastical Authorities in 1606. Consequently, on the same year, a separate municipal building/hall was erected for the community. San Ildefonso de Toledo became the patron saint of the town. Fray Pedro de Talavera was the first parish priest from 1606 – 1608. It was also in 1606, when the first book on baptism or “Libro de Baptismorum” commenced.</p>', 'history', '#Tan-ay', 1, 9, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(32, 'TRANSFER FROM INALSAN TO SAN ANTONIO (Pantay) in 1620', 'transfer-from-inalsan-to-san-antonio-pantay-in-1620', '<p><strong>Transfer from Inalsan to San Antonio (Pantay) in 1620</strong></p><p>In 1620, the town was transferred from Inalsan to San Antonio (now Pantay, a sitio of Brgy. Tandang Kutyo) when the Aetas burned the church which was made of cogon. San Antonio was considered as “ikalawang bayan”.</p><p>Some twenty (20) years later, San Antonio (Pantay) was also destroyed like the old town, Inalsan. People were forced to transfer to another place, the present site of the municipality. The town at its current location was founded in 1640.&nbsp;</p><p><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></p>', 'history', '#Brgy.TandangKutyo', 1, 10, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(33, 'LUTONG PUGON', 'lutong-pugon', '<p><img src=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-XJzpSq40tig/Wu8MEFNOXkI/AAAAAAAADFA/3EoadxQdq8USjyh7J_aHgU4chWZ-F5ERACLcBGAs/s1600/DSC_4319.jpg\" alt=\"Image result for lutong pugon\" data-mce-src=\"https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-XJzpSq40tig/Wu8MEFNOXkI/AAAAAAAADFA/3EoadxQdq8USjyh7J_aHgU4chWZ-F5ERACLcBGAs/s1600/DSC_4319.jpg\" width=\"313\" height=\"251\"></p><p>This little out of the way place is very nice. &nbsp;It\'s located in Sampaloc in the mountainous area of Tanay. &nbsp;Outdoor setting with limited parking. &nbsp;They serve wood fired pizza. &nbsp;The pizza was tasty and crisp. &nbsp;It took quite a while to get the pizza, so if you\'re in a hurry don\'t go here. &nbsp;Nice flowers all around and nice outside views. &nbsp;The place is owned by an artist who also has his house on the property. &nbsp;Word of warning: &nbsp;Do not drink the filtered water. &nbsp;Get bottled water. &nbsp;I drank the filtered water and was in the ER 2 days later. &nbsp;Pizza was good though. &nbsp;I\'d go back.</p><div><span class=\"_2iem\">Address : Sitio Masanting, Sampaloc</span></div><div><span class=\"_2iem\">Tanay, Rizal</span></div><div><span class=\"_2iem\"><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></span></div><div><span class=\"_2iem\">https://en.yelp.com.ph/biz/lutong-pugon-tanay</span></div>', 'cuisine', '#Pizza', 1, 3, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 5, 1),
(34, 'PASEO RIZAL MAYAGAY', 'paseo-rizal-mayagay', '<p><img src=\"https://media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-s/05/4f/61/64/paseo-rizal.jpg\" alt=\"Image result for paseo tanay rizal\" data-mce-src=\"https://media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-s/05/4f/61/64/paseo-rizal.jpg\" width=\"413\" height=\"251\"></p><div class=\"title\">Good for Kids, Large groups, Romantic, Families with children</div><div class=\"title\"><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></div><div class=\"title\">https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Restaurant_Review-g2336235-d6024245-Reviews-Paseo_Rizal-Tanay_Rizal_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon.html</div>', 'cuisine', '#PaseoRizalRestaurany', 1, 4, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 5, 1),
(35, 'THE RUSTIC ART OF JO FLORENDO', 'the-rustic-art-of-jo-florendo', '<p><img src=\"http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/files/2013/02/t0211florendo-art_feat3_1.jpg\" data-mce-src=\"http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/files/2013/02/t0211florendo-art_feat3_1.jpg\" width=\"416\" height=\"221\"></p><p><img src=\"http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/files/2013/02/t0211florendo-art_feat3_2-300x237.jpg\" data-mce-src=\"http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/files/2013/02/t0211florendo-art_feat3_2-300x237.jpg\"></p><p>To grow up in Tanay, Rizal, just like in its neighboring town of Angono, home to many of the country’s great artists, is to learn how to draw and paint its rustic beauty—modest houses under a mango tree; golden rice stalks dancing in the wind; bountiful fish frolicking on the pond.</p><p>Angelito “Jo” Florendo is a Tanay painter who’s probably a cut above many. As a young boy, he grew up amid oil paint, acrylic and aquarelle under the tutelage of Tanay painter Martin Catalos and watercolorist Jun Tiongco.</p><p><br><br>Read more:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/89315/the-rustic-art-of-jo-florendo/#ixzz5SVA0jlqF\" data-mce-href=\"https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/89315/the-rustic-art-of-jo-florendo/#ixzz5SVA0jlqF\">https://lifestyle.inquirer.net/89315/the-rustic-art-of-jo-florendo/#ixzz5SVA0jlqF</a>&nbsp;<br>Follow us:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ec.tynt.com/b/rw?id=bSAw-mF-0r4Q-4acwqm_6r&amp;u=inquirerdotnet\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-mce-href=\"http://ec.tynt.com/b/rw?id=bSAw-mF-0r4Q-4acwqm_6r&amp;u=inquirerdotnet\">@inquirerdotnet on Twitter</a>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<a href=\"http://ec.tynt.com/b/rf?id=bSAw-mF-0r4Q-4acwqm_6r&amp;u=inquirerdotnet\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-mce-href=\"http://ec.tynt.com/b/rf?id=bSAw-mF-0r4Q-4acwqm_6r&amp;u=inquirerdotnet\">inquirerdotnet on Facebook</a></p>', 'arts', '#joFlorendo', 1, 1, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(36, 'ARTIST PROFILE : Q&A WITH JOEL MASAYA AND HIS FILIPISM ART', 'artist-profile-qa-with-joel-masaya-and-his-filipism-art', '<p>When an artist says he is into Filipinism, one automatically associates it with pastoral life and rural Philippines. However, Filipinism in the past was viewed as very limiting but now; it is more of a blessing –artists like Joel Masaya gives his art a little spin by capturing the image with his brushes rather than a lifeless colorful stroke.</p><p>Joel Masaya’s art breathes new life into it, and makes it a way to celebrate life by utilizing the riotous colors and complex forms naturally abounding in these islands. This is what Joel Masaya has been doing in his paintings. This art form is a way of showing the real identity of the artist into their works as a Filipino.&nbsp; He paints to preserve the life of the past and the forgotten culture long ago silenced.</p><p>Joel Masaya is an active member of Tanay Art Group founded by Tam Austria and Jun Tiongco. He retired from textile designing and is now a full time artist–100% devoted to his art. His series of mother and child are a tribute to the master artist, Tam Austria. His works are in the collection of prominent art collectors here and abroad.</p><p><img src=\"https://jennysserendipity.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/joel-masaya-7.jpg?w=676&amp;h=507\" alt=\"Homage to the Master Sa Piling ni Nanay  Acrylic on Canvas, 2014 Private Collection \" data-mce-src=\"https://jennysserendipity.files.wordpress.com/2015/02/joel-masaya-7.jpg?w=676&amp;h=507\" width=\"391\" height=\"261\"></p><p>(Homage to the Master,&nbsp;Sa Piling ni Nanay,&nbsp;Acrylic on Canvas, 2014<br>Private Collection)</p><p>https://jennysserendipity.com/2015/02/08/artist-profile-qa-with-joel-masaya-and-his-filipinism-art/</p>', 'arts', '#Paints', 1, 2, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 3, 1),
(37, 'CAFE KATARINA', 'cafe-katarina', '<p><img src=\"https://rainbowanders.files.wordpress.com/2017/10/img_7283.jpg?w=1920\" alt=\"Image result for cafe katerina\" data-mce-src=\"https://rainbowanders.files.wordpress.com/2017/10/img_7283.jpg?w=1920\" width=\"437\" height=\"242\"></p><div class=\"title\">Restaurant features : Takeout, Outdoor Seating, Seating, Waitstaff, Reservations, Wheelchair Accessible</div><div class=\"title\"><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></div><div class=\"title\"><div class=\"title\">Location and Contact Information</div><div class=\"content\"><ul class=\"detailsContent\"><li><div class=\"detail\">Address:&nbsp;<span class=\"format_address\"><span class=\"street-address\">Marcos Highway, Sitio Mayagay1 Sampaloc</span>&nbsp;|&nbsp;<span class=\"extended-address\">Sitio Mayagay1 Sampaloc</span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"locality\">Tanay, Luzon 1980,&nbsp;</span><span class=\"country-name\">Philippines</span></span></div></li><li><div class=\"detail\">Location:&nbsp;Asia&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Philippines&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Luzon&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Calabarzon Region&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Rizal Province&nbsp;&nbsp;&gt;&nbsp; Tanay</div></li></ul><p><br data-mce-bogus=\"1\"></p><p>https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Restaurant_Review-g2336235-d8144595-Reviews-Cafe_Katerina-Tanay_Rizal_Province_Calabarzon_Region_Luzon.html</p></div></div>', 'cuisine', '#KainNaInCafeKatarina', 1, 5, '2018-10-03 10:58:18', 5, 1),
